Abstract

Brief, informative, clear summary of the report and main conclusions.

Introduction

Saanich Inlet is cool. It is a seasonally anoxic fjord [1]. Other stuff about Sannich

Information on OTUs vs.ASVs

Using these data, we investigated how microbial communities differ across depth and oxygen gradients in Saanich Inlet with particular focus on the unclassified domain (you will have a different taxon than this). The unclassified domain is of interest because In addition, we determine if and how different sequence analysis pipelines impact these biological conclusions.

Methods

We have these data collected in this way for use in this project [1,2] Sequences were processed using either mothur [3] or QIIME2 [4]

Analysis was completed in R v3.4.3 [5] using the following packages.

Results

This example section is just to give you an idea of some of the analyses that you could do with these data. Please do not follow this section exactly! We will only show analyses with the mothur data in these examples and the plots are not perfect (axes labels, etc). Let your taxon of interest and own biological questions guide the analysis you do!

Data cleaning

Data were loaded into R.

load("data/mothur_phyloseq.RData")

Samples were rarefied/normalized to 100,000 sequences per sample to facilitate comparisons between samples. A random seed was set to ensure reproducibility.

set.seed(4832)
m.norm = rarefy_even_depth(mothur, sample.size=100000)
## You set `rngseed` to FALSE. Make sure you've set & recorded
##  the random seed of your session for reproducibility.
## See `?set.seed`
## ...
## 614OTUs were removed because they are no longer 
## present in any sample after random subsampling
## ...

Rarefied counts were converted to relative abundance percentages.

m.perc = transform_sample_counts(m.norm, function(x) 100 * x/sum(x))

How does microbial community structure change with depth and oxygen concentration?

Alpha-diversity

Alpha-diversity and richness were calculated for the total community in R.

# Calculate
m.alpha = estimate_richness(m.norm, measures = c("Chao1", "Shannon"))

# Combine these data with the rest of the geochemical data so that we have 1 data frame to work with in future plots. Note use of the rownames_to_column function which mutates the dataframes to have a new column containing the row names data (because the tidyverse doesn't understand row names).
m.meta.alpha = full_join(rownames_to_column(m.alpha), rownames_to_column(data.frame(m.perc@sam_data)), by = "rowname")

m.meta.alpha

Linear model

  subset_taxa(Domain=="unknown") %>% 
  tax_glom(taxrank = 'Domain') %>%
  psmelt() %>%

  lm(Abundance ~ Depth_m, .) %>%

Notes after initial report checks

Figures

  • Smoothers (i.e. geom_smooth) are not statistics equivalent to linear models. They are merely meant to help visualize the data. And if the smoother doesnt show a trend you want to then test, you dont necessary need to include it.
  • Figures should have a title and full text legend below the figure, similar to how you would see in a published paper, not just a title and the legend that ggplot makes for color, size, etc. This means you will not need to use labs(title = )
  • If you are having difficulty using a continuous variable as color and seeing any patterns, consider log transforming it and using that as the color variable.
  • You do not always need to show all the data. Consider only showing the significant OTUs/ASVs in figures. Think about the journal articles you have read and how they use figures to support conclusions, not to just show all the data.
  • Note the labels of axes, legends, etc. The defauly ggplot ones are not usually the best.

Results and discussion

  • Conclusions should be supported by a p-value (if available) not a plot alone. The plot is just a visual tool, not statistics.
  • P-values should be reported in the text or in a table. It is not sufficient to only state that a group of them were < 0.05.

Other

  • mothur is all lowercase. QIIME is all uppercase since it is an acronym.
  • If you provide your report as an .Rmd, then the code does not have to be present in the knit document (though it can be). However, if you provide a Word/PDF document only, the code must be included so that it can be assessed. Within the report as a supplemental file totally okay.

Multi-panel figures

Of interest to several groups may be how to make multi-panel figures. We can do this easily with the cowplot package.

library(cowplot)
## 
## Attaching package: 'cowplot'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     ggsave

For example, we will make a multi-panel figure of alpha-diversity and oxygen across depths in the mothur data. First, we create the plots and save them as named objects plot1 and plot2

plot1 = m.meta.alpha %>% 
  
ggplot(aes(x=Depth_m, y=Shannon)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y="Shannon's diversity index", x="Depth (m)")
plot2 = m.meta.alpha %>% 

ggplot(aes(x=O2_uM, y=Shannon)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_line() +
  labs(y="Shannon's diversity index", x="Oxygen (uM)")

Then we can plot these two plots together and give A, B, etc labels with plot_grid

plot_grid(plot1, plot2, labels=c("A", "B"))

And we can change the orientation with the number of columns (ncol) or rows (nrow). Or change the relative widths or heights of plots (rel_widths, rel_heights).

plot_grid(plot1, plot2, labels=c("A", "B"), ncol=1, rel_heights = c(0.5,1))

Though this doesnt really make sense for the plots above. Just an example!

Figure size

It may also be useful to decrease figure sizes. You can do so by modifying a code chunk as in the following; size is given in inches.

```{r fig.height=3, fig.width=3}

```
